cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this specification, please cite it as below."
type: software
title: "Agent Context Memory: A Governance-First Specification for AI Agent Context Memory"
abstract: >
  ACM (Agent Context Memory) is a specification for governance-first context memory
  in autonomous AI agent systems. It covers the full scope of agent memory —
  episodic, semantic, and working memory as prior work establishes — and adds a
  governance layer no prior specification defines. The novel contribution is the
  Mandate Gate (Principle 1): a pre-work mandate, authored by the principal, must
  exist in the agent's memory before any session of work is valid. This makes
  context memory governance-first rather than capability-first. Prior models
  (MemGPT, CoALA, Generative Agents) treat memory as a working resource the agent
  draws from during work. ACM treats memory as a precondition — the gate that
  determines whether work can begin at all. ACM also defines three memory tiers
  organized by trust level (intent / trace / evidence), structural capture-author
  separation, and convergence as a memory-level property. ACM is the operationalization
  of Principles of Earned Autonomy (PEA) for the context memory design problem.
  The reference implementation is the .trail/ directory pattern.
